 NEW Delhi, May 7 (bdnews24.com/AFP) Reliance Dhirubhai Group Chairman Anil Ambani (R) walks with officials as he leaves the Supreme Court in New Delhi on May 7, 2010, after hearing judgements in a legal dispute involving the supply of natural gas. India's Supreme Court ruled in favour of India's richest man, Mukesh Ambani, as it settled his feud with his brother Anil over a family deal to divide the country's biggest gas field. -- PHOTO: AFP NEW DELHI - INDIA'S Supreme Court ruled in favour of India's richest man, Mukesh Ambani, on Friday as it settled his feud with his brother Anil over a family deal to divide the country's biggest gas field. The court threw out a contract between the estranged siblings involving the supply of natural gas from the Krishna-Godavari basin off the east Indian coast. Mr Anil had demanded the honouring of the 2005 agreement brokered by their mother that would allow his company to buy gas for 17 years from the KG basin owned by Mr Mukesh at a price lower than the one set by the government. Mr Mukesh sought to have this deal annulled in a legal fight that has captivated India with its mix of incredible wealth and family feuding. Reflecting the decision, shares in Mr Anil's group, Reliance Natural Resources, plunged 18.29 per cent to 55.85 rupees (S$1.72) on the Mumbai stock exchange. Shares in Mr Mukesh's Reliance industries rose 4.56 per cent to 1,057 after the verdict. The seeds of the feud lie in a deal between the brothers slicing up the Reliance telecoms-to-energy empire built by their rags-to-riches father Dhirubhai Ambani, who died in 2002 leaving no will. In the asset split, Mr Mukesh kept the oil, gas and petrochemicals businesses of the group's flagship Reliance Industries. Mr Anil got Reliance Energy, one of India's biggest power utility firms, thephone company and finance arm. Under the terms of the 2005 gas agreement brokered by their mother, Mr Anil would receive gas supplied by Mr Mukesh at a price 44 per cent lower than t